Project: Supervised Learning - Cars4U - Pre-Owned Car Price Prediction¶

Context¶

There is a huge demand for used cars in the Indian Market today. As sales of new cars have slowed down in the recent past, the pre-owned car market has continued to grow over the past years and is larger than the new car market now. Cars4U is a budding tech start-up that aims to find footholes in this market.

In 2018-19, while new car sales were recorded at 3.6 million units, around 4 million second-hand cars were bought and sold. There is a slowdown in new car sales and that could mean that the demand is shifting towards the pre-owned market. In fact, some car sellers replace their old cars with pre-owned cars instead of buying new ones.

Unlike new cars, where price and supply are fairly deterministic and managed by OEMs (Original Equipment Manufacturer / except for dealership level discounts which come into play only in the last stage of the customer journey), used cars are very different beasts with huge uncertainty in both pricing and supply. Keeping this in mind, the pricing scheme of these used cars becomes important in order to grow in the market.

Objective¶

We have to come up with a pricing model that can effectively predict the price of used cars and can help the business in devising profitable strategies using differential pricing. We also need to explore and visualize the dataset, build a linear regression model to predict the prices of used cars, and generate a set of insights and recommendations that will help the business.

Key Questions¶

  1. What are the key factors influencing the price of a pre-owned cars?
  2. Is there a good predictive model for the pre-owned car pricing? What does the performance assessment look like for such a model?

Data Description¶

The data contains the different attributes of used cars sold in different locations. The detailed data dictionary is given below.

Data Dictionary¶

  • S.No.: Serial number
  • Name: Name of the car which includes brand name and model name
  • Location: Location in which the car is being sold or is available for purchase (cities)
  • Year: Manufacturing year of the car
  • Kilometers_driven: The total kilometers driven in the car by the previous owner(s) in km
  • Fuel_Type: The type of fuel used by the car (Petrol, Diesel, Electric, CNG, LPG)
  • Transmission: The type of transmission used by the car (Automatic/Manual)
  • Owner: Type of ownership
  • Mileage: The standard mileage offered by the car company in kmpl or km/kg
  • Engine: The displacement volume of the engine in CC
  • Power: The maximum power of the engine in bhp
  • Seats: The number of seats in the car
  • New_Price: The price of a new car of the same model in INR Lakhs (1 Lakh INR = 100,000 INR)
  • Price: The price of the used car in INR Lakhs

Removing the units for Numerical Columns¶

  • New_Price: Convert the New_Price to Lakh only, it has both Lakh and Crores INR units
  • Milage, Power, Engine: We need to just remove the units and no translation is required.
In [16]:
def inr_to_num(val):
    """
    Convert a value such as INR 12.5 Lakh or INR 12.5 Cr to Lakh
    Return only the number part as float
    1 Cr = 100 Lakh
    """
    if isinstance(val, str):
        multiplier = 1
        if val.strip().endswith('Lakh'):
            multiplier = 1
        elif val.strip().endswith('Cr'):
            multiplier = 100
        return float(val.replace('Lakh', '').replace('Cr', '').strip()) * multiplier
    else:
        return np.nan

def str_to_num(val):
    """
    Remove units from values and return just a float number
    Examples: 26.6 km/kg => 26.6 or 126.2 bhp => 126.2 or 1234 CC => 1234.0
    Return only the number as float
    No multiplier or translation is performed.
    """
    if isinstance(val, str):
        num = []
        chars = list(val)
        for c in chars:
            if c.isdigit() or c == '.':
                num.append(c)
        return float(''.join(num))
    else:
        return np.nan

Split the Name column to Brand and Model¶

Since the data description says Name consists of Brand name and model name, we can create two columns out of this information, one column for Brand and the model, second for the model variant. Our experience shows that car prices greatly vary based on its brand, model and its variant. Unfortunately there are too many variants, hence we are going to ignore the variant part for now. Also model variant informaiton to some extent encoded in other columns such as Transmission, Seats, Engine and Power features.

From the Name column, it would be sufficient if we capture just Brand and model info and find a grouping strategy to categorize them to reduce the number of distinct values in the set.

In [23]:
def extract_brand_n_model(val):
    """
    Split a car name to its brand-model and variant information
    Return a tuple (brand model, model variant)
    """
    parts = val.split(" ")
    return (" ".join(parts[0:2]), " ".join(parts[2:]))

In [29]:
def cal_price_range(key):
    """
    Given a Brand and Model type return a custom category based on median price range
    Return P1, P6, P11, etc. where P1 means price within 1 Lakh, P6 means within 6 Lakhs etc.
    """
    val = brand_model_mean[key]
    # We are taking 3 Lakhs as step from one group to the next
    for i in range (1, 125, 3):
        if val <= i:
            return 'P' + str(i)
    return 'P0'

# function to plot a boxplot and a histogram along the same scale.
def box_hist_plot(data, feature, figsize=(12, 7), bins=10):
    """
    This will show a box and hist plot in a column alignment, For hist plot kde is set to True

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    figsize: size of figure (default (12,7))
    """
    # creating the 2 subplots
    f2, (ax_box2, ax_hist2) = plt.subplots(
        nrows=2,  # Number of rows of the subplot grid= 2
        sharex=True,  # x-axis will be shared among all subplots
        gridspec_kw={"height_ratios": (0.25, 0.75)},
        figsize=figsize,
    )  
    # boxplot will be created and a star will indicate the mean value of the column
    sns.boxplot(data=data, x=feature, ax=ax_box2, showmeans=True, color="violet")  
    # For hist plot
    sns.histplot(data=data, x=feature, kde=True, bins=bins, ax=ax_hist2) 
    # Add mean to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].mean(), color="green", linestyle="--") 
    # Add median to the histogram
    ax_hist2.axvline(data[feature].median(), color="black", linestyle="-")

  • Engine_Num more or less normally distributed but it has right skew
  • Also there are 36 missing values.

The best way to treat the missing value in this case would be pickup a similar cars (make and model) if available and calculate the mean and assign the same to impute the missing value. If no similar car exists then we can resort the the mean of entire column.

The same logic can be applied to impute the missing values for Mileage and Power.

In order to reuse this strategy we are going to write two python functions that will help us to so as follows

In [51]:
# calculate a missing feature based on a similar car or its model
def cal_feature_mean_by_car(feature, name):
    """
    If an exact car name exists in the dataset it will return the mean of those values where the feature is not null
    If the exact car name does not match then it will return the mean of similar car model where the feature is not null
    If that also does not exists then it will return the mean of the feaure
    It return the mean with as float with 2 decimal places
    
    feature: e.g. Engine_Num
    name: e.g. Maruti Wagon R Vx
    """
    feature_mean_by_name = df[df[feature].notnull() & (df[feature] > 0)].groupby('Name')[feature].mean()
    feature_mean_by_model = df[df[feature].notnull() & (df[feature] > 0)].groupby('Brand_Model')[feature].mean()
    feature_mean = round(df[feature].mean(),2)
    if name in feature_mean_by_name.keys().to_list():
        return round(feature_mean_by_name[name],2)
    else:
        parts = name.split(" ")
        bm = " ".join(parts[0:2])
        if bm in feature_mean_by_model.keys().to_list():
            return round(feature_mean_by_model[bm],2)
        else:
            return feature_mean

In [54]:
def impute_zero_or_nan_by_car_mean(feature):
    """
    It takes a feature such as Engine_Num and identify the indexes where its value is 0 or nan
    and then replaces it with mean by calculating using function cal_feature_mean_by_car
    This way it imputes the missing value closest to actual data for the given car
    """
    for idx in df[(df[feature] == 0) | df[feature].isnull()].index.to_list():
        car_name = df.at[idx, 'Name']
        df.at[idx, feature] = cal_feature_mean_by_car(feature, car_name)
        print('Imputed ', feature, ' at ', idx, ' with ', df.at[idx, feature], ' for car ', car_name)

In [70]:
# function to create bar plot with percent labels
def bar_perc_plot(data, feature):
    """
    Barplot with percentage at the top

    data: dataframe
    feature: dataframe column
    """

    # calculate the fig width dynamically
    total = len(data[feature]) 
    count = data[feature].nunique()
    plt.figure(figsize=(count + 1, 5))

    plt.xticks(rotation=90, fontsize=15)
    ax = sns.countplot(
        data=data,
        x=feature,
        palette="Paired",
        # Sort the bars from high to low
        order=data[feature].value_counts().sort_values(ascending=False).index,
    )

    for bar in ax.patches:
        # percentage of each class of the category
        label = "{:.2f}%".format(100 * bar.get_height() / total)  
        x = bar.get_x() + bar.get_width() / 2  # width of the plot
        y = bar.get_height()  # height of the plot

        # annotate the percentage
        ax.annotate(
            label,
            (x, y),
            ha="center",
            va="center",
            size=12,
            xytext=(0, 5),
            textcoords="offset points",
        ) 

    plt.show();  # show the plot

Sometimes car prices do vary based on a location, the same model may cost little different between Mumbai and Kolkata. We can group these cities based on their median car price range, if a location has higher median prices of cars then generally people in that city are ready to pay little higher prices based on demand and supply situation.

def med_price_zone_label(location):
    """
    Given a location return a median price zone
    
    location: City
    """
    if med_price_zones[location] > 6:
        return 'Median>6L'
    elif 5 < med_price_zones[location] < 6:
        return 'Median5-6L'
    elif 4 < med_price_zones[location] < 5:
        return 'Median4-5L'
    if med_price_zones[location] < 4:
        return 'Median<4L'

Measuring the performance of LinearRegression Model¶

In [105]:
# to check model performance
from sklearn.metrics import mean_absolute_error, mean_squared_error, r2_score

# predictors: independent variables
# target: dependent variable
# predictions: prediction by model
# model: regressor

# function to compute adjusted R-squared
def adj_r2_score(predictors, targets, predictions):
    r2 = r2_score(targets, predictions)
    n = predictors.shape[0]
    k = predictors.shape[1]
    return 1 - ((1 - r2) * (n - 1) / (n - k - 1))

# function to compute different metrics to check performance of a regression model
def model_perf_report(model, predictors, target):

    # predicting using the independent variables
    pred = model.predict(predictors)

    r2 = r2_score(target, pred)  # to compute R-squared
    adjr2 = adj_r2_score(predictors, target, pred)  # to compute adjusted R-squared
    rmse = mean_squared_error(target, pred, squared= False)  # to compute RMSE
    mae = mean_absolute_error(target, pred)  # to compute MAE

    # creating a dataframe of metrics
    df_perf = pd.DataFrame(
        {
            "RMSE": rmse,
            "MAE": mae,
            "R-squared": r2,
            "Adj. R-squared": adjr2
        },
        index=[0]
    )

    return df_perf

Trying with PolynomialFeatures¶

We will try with PolynomialFeatures to see if that gives a better $R^2$ value. If there are interdependencies among independent variable PolynomialFeatures may give a better $R^2$ value. But it may overfit as we are increasing the number of features significantly.

In [111]:
#Adding interaction terms

from sklearn.preprocessing import PolynomialFeatures
from sklearn import linear_model

poly = PolynomialFeatures(degree=2, interaction_only=True)
X1_train2 = poly.fit_transform(X1_train)
X1_test2 = poly.fit_transform(X1_test)

poly_clf = linear_model.LinearRegression()

poly_clf.fit(X1_train2, y1_train)

#In sample (training) R^2 will always improve with the number of variables!
print(poly_clf.score(X1_train2, y1_train))

0.9379128563161803

PolynomialFeatures is able to explain almost 94% of a variation in the training data, which is really good!

Conclusions¶

  • With the given features used_cars_data.csv it is possible to build a Supervised Learning model that can predict the price of a pre-owned cars with $R^2$ value of 0.81.
  • If a simplar model is desired that does not include car Names and Locations due to space time complexity then a Liner Regression model with Polynomial Features would be best.
  • But if space time complexity is not an issue then we need to feature engineer Name and Locations and use a simple LinerRegression model.
  • In order to increase the performance of the models more data need to be collected which can give more quantititive information on the model variant and the condition of the car.
  • Features such as Safety Rating, Leather Seats, Car Electronics features, Condition Rating (Mechanical/Body) etc. need to be added and then models can be trained to better predit the price.
  • But it seems with right feature sets LinerRegression can predict pre-owned car prices with very good accuracy. And Cars4U can improve its car pricing and efficiency with these type of predictive model. Which can bring efficiency in the system, reduce cost and improve sales and operating profit to a great extent!
